text: Why is this a brilliant teaser despite how much it shows? Because aside from that shot at the end (and maybe one in the middle, I'll have to go back and check) you don't see Dr. Strange in his signature outfit, and you don't see him using any magic. It really is just a hint to whet the appetite, and I love it!  I just hope that the next trailer shows Stephen doing a little bit more in costume. I don't want them to show me the whole movie, but I also don't want to go see the movie and only see Doctor Strange in that one shot from the end of the trailer, and that one highway scene I keep gifs of behind the scenes footage for on tumblr. As it stands right now, I'm hyped. If you're not, then you're doing this whole "fan" thing wrong.

text: First Impressions: As long as they don't pull that Thor bs, and make magic "advanced technology," I'll be completely on bored with this movie. It seems to follow the comics well in terms of origin story. I am worried about how some actors will handle the strange/aloof/eccentric nature of their characters. Im hoping it's not a generic "superhero story;" being different is the only way this movie will work. Also the lack of a featured antagonist is worrying. Although, I'm glad that the trailer didn't do what every other trailer does, and give away 99% of the movie. Also, the settings look interesting. It is also refreshing to see these settings in the overplayed superhero movie genre. Also, I'm confused about how much, or how little the abstract nature of magic will be in the movie. All in all I'm very much intrigued by this movie, and excitedly anticipate it's release.

text: I like how everyone is confused in the comment section. Personally, I've been studying the occult and spiritism for a while now and I was worried this film will deeply entrench more misinformation in the public eye about these ancient teachings. The trailer looks amazing, and so far the message about the scope of reality not being all that it seems is spot on,  it's no accident that it sounds like inception or matrix because those concepts were inspired by the idea that there are unseen forces and powers at work behind the veil of our culture and there are ways to tap into them, here's to hoping this movie is the kick our generation needs to start thinking differently.

I will see this movie because I like stories about changes/changing perceptions, including Inception or the Matrix or other such movies...Doctor Strange is essentially derivative, but essentiallyÂ ALL art is derivative when you really look at it. ItÂ mightÂ beÂ just new to you, but it'sÂ ALWAYS not new to history. The same themesÂ justÂ pop up again and again. So, relax your sphincters (some of you) and enjoy this interpretation of this sub-genre. No need to get all in a tizzy. text: I'll just copy a comment that I saw today on Facebook, because I think it's really informative (for people not knowing these things already), and well put:  Christopher Kidman: "This will help those folks that have pointed out the Inception similarities. Doctor Strange is a mind-bending, psychedelic, and dark comic series. He is a practitioner of a mystic art form in which they can travel thru the very fabric of time and space. He can snap his fingers and transport The Avengers to another dimension. He's like the Bulk Beings in Interstellar. He can live and manipulate beyond the four dimensions we know. With powers like that, it would make him crucial for Infinity War. That "Inception" scene that you are referencing to is not the same as it was in Inception. It was quite different, just like it was in Upside Down. The visuals may be similar, but it's how I would expect a live action adaptation to look like. As much as I loved Inception, it wasn't all that original. It borrowed from The Thirteenth Floor, The Dark City, The Matrix, Videodrome, eXistenZ, and Paprika. A similar scene was in an earlier draft of X-Men: First Class, but the script was rewritten due to Inception's trailer being released. In a sense, all the mentioned films above were influenced by Doctor Strange comics, which have been around since 1963."

Marvel characters have always been safe compared to DC's however Marvel can explore a vast array of characters and topics while DC can't and that's why DC is failing. text: Even ignoring the white-washing, this looks pretty boring. Pretty special effects are great, but the tone isn't anything special or unique. It has the inception, batman begins vibe, but without anything new. It has magic, but it doesn't feel grounded or real. The story wasn't really pinned down except dude gets hurt, finds a mentor, wants to learn magic, but it's usually fine to hold back in the first trailer. But this gets me as excited as Batman v. Superman's first trailer did, aka, bored as heck. I think it will be a pretty movie, but I think all the magic and personality went into Guardians of the Galaxy, all the action and drama went to Winter Soldier, and this is just not anything more than a few tropes and archetypes we've seen again and again strung together.  Not ignoring the white-washing now, it is a red-flag for how sensitive the director/casting directors are to audience desires and perceptions. That same audience blindness I saw in the casting of Lex Luthor in Batman v. Superman, and on the Marvel side, in Joss Whedon's tap-twist in Age of Ultron. It's a bad sign for the characters, their nuances, and how they might develop. I'm not saying they couldn't cast Tilda Swinton, but they also (upping the supernatural and mind-bending factor) could have casted a few people as equally as her to play that one character, an Asian amongst them, and had them rotate equally to bend Strange's perceptions (and the audiences as well) as to who this person really is. Appearances are deceiving could have been a trope they played with, and baring casting an Asian (in an obviously Asian role) this is the second best option.

text: One of the coolest thing about this trailer is when we see Doctor Strange's soul being separated from his body. Not because of the act itself, but by the huge clue I think it gives. The color of his soul is orange. If this is so, it could give a huge clue to where the Soul Stone is. There's a character who's ability is to being able to see every soul. The color orange is very prevalent with this character and that's Heimdall. What if the Soul Stone is an actual soul, Heimdall's soul. It  would explain why the Infinity Gauntlet slot for the orange stone is not only bigger than the rest, but it's appearance is more like an energy source instead of a stone like the rest. Would make a sense as the Soul would be at the center of Space, Reality, Power, Mind and Time. If the stone on Doctor Strange necklace is an Infinity stone, then it's probably the Time Stone and not the Soul Stone like some have suggested. Heimdall's appearance in Thor's vision on Avengers: AoU made me suspicious, but now I'm almost certain this could be a thing. Other clues lie within Heimdall himself as his new armor has an orange stone in it, his eyes are orange, and his name starts with an H. That last one is super vague, but if Thanos name was meant as a clue to the location of all Stones, then maybe that's a thing. Tessaract, Aether, Orb, Scepter. We would be missing H and N. So Heimdall and Necklace would fit. Just a fun thought to have while we wait for the next movies. If this is the case though, Thor's third movie will be something to look forward to.
author: Neophenom

text: >> Catechism of the Catholic Church <<  III. "You Shall Have No Other Gods Before Me"  Divination and magic  2115 God can reveal the future to his prophets or to other saints. Still, a sound Christian attitude consists in putting oneself confidently into the hands of Providence for whatever concerns the future, and giving up all unhealthy curiosity about it. Improvidence, however, can constitute a lack of responsibility.  2116 All forms of divination are to be rejected: recourse to Satan or demons, conjuring up the dead or other practices falsely supposed to "unveil" the future. Consulting horoscopes, astrology, palm reading, interpretation of omens and lots, the phenomena of clairvoyance, and recourse to mediums all conceal a desire for power over time, history, and, in the last analysis, other human beings, as well as a wish to conciliate hidden powers. They contradict the honor, respect, and loving fear that we owe to God alone.  2117 All practices of magic or sorcery, by which one attempts to tame occult powers, so as to place them at one's service and have a supernatural power over others - even if this were for the sake of restoring their health - are gravely contrary to the virtue of religion. These practices are even more to be condemned when accompanied by the intention of harming someone, or when they have recourse to the intervention of demons. Wearing charms is also reprehensible. Spiritism often implies divination or magical practices; the Church for her part warns the faithful against it. Recourse to so-called traditional cures does not justify either the invocation of evil powers or the exploitation of another's credulity.
